04781nam a22006255i 9780822391029DE-B159720220302035458.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220302t20092009ncu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808223910297 a10.1515/97808223910292doi  a(DE-B1597)553560  a(OCoLC)1224278955  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ancucUS-NC 4aPN56.C63 7aHIS0170002bisacsh04a820.9/353809541 aArondekar, Anjali, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aFor the Record :bOn Sexuality and the Colonial Archive in India /cAnjali Arondekar; ed. by Robyn Wiegman, Caren Kaplan, Inderpal Grewal. 1aDurham : bDuke University Press, c[2009] 4c©2009  a1 online resource (228 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aNext Wave: New Directions in Women's Studies : 4400tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tPreface -- tIntroduction. Without A Trace -- tOne. A Secret Report: Richard Burton’s Colonial Anthropology -- tTwo. Subject to Sodomy: The Case of Colonial India -- tThree. Archival Attachments: The Story of an India-Rubber Dildo -- tFour. In the Wake of 1857: Rudyard Kipling’s Mutiny Papers -- tCoda. Passing Returns -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aAnjali Arondekar considers the relationship between sexuality and the colonial archive by posing the following questions: Why does sexuality (still) seek its truth in the historical archive? What are the spatial and temporal logics that compel such a return? And conversely, what kind of “archive” does such a recuperative hermeneutics produce? Rather than render sexuality’s relationship to the colonial archive through the preferred lens of historical invisibility (which would presume that there is something about sexuality that is lost or silent and needs to “come out”), Arondekar engages sexuality’s recursive traces within the colonial archive against and through our very desire for access.The logic and the interpretive resources of For the Record arise out of two entangled and minoritized historiographies: one in South Asian studies and the other in queer/sexuality studies. Focusing on late colonial India, Arondekar examines the spectacularization of sexuality in anthropology, law, literature, and pornography from 1843 until 1920. By turning to materials and/or locations that are familiar to most scholars of queer and subaltern studies, Arondekar considers sexuality at the center of the colonial archive rather than at its margins. Each chapter addresses a form of archival loss, troped either in a language of disappearance or paucity, simulacrum or detritus: from Richard Burton’s missing report on male brothels in Karáchi (1845) to a failed sodomy prosecution in Northern India, Queen Empress v. Khairati (1884), and from the ubiquitous India-rubber dildos found in colonial pornography of the mid-to-late nineteenth century to the archival detritus of Kipling’s stories about the Indian Mutiny of 1857.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aColonies in literature. 0aHomosexuality in literature. 0aLiterature and history. 0aPostcolonialism in literature. 0aPostcolonialismzIndia. 7aHISTORY / Asia / India & South Asia.2bisacsh1 aGrewal, Inderpal, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aKaplan, Caren, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aWiegman, Robyn, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDuke University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311071183740uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780822391029zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780822391029423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780822391029/original  a978-3-11